description:
## Location
firmware/bridge-zephyr/subsys/lichen/lichen_util.c:21-24

## Finding
The SHA-256 helper chains `tc_sha256_init`, `tc_sha256_update`, and `tc_sha256_final` in a single `if` statement:
```c
if (tc_sha256_init(&state) != TC_CRYPTO_SUCCESS ||
    tc_sha256_update(&state, input, inlen) != TC_CRYPTO_SUCCESS ||
    tc_sha256_final(output, &state) != TC_CRYPTO_SUCCESS) {
    ret = -EIO;
}
```

All failures return `-EIO`, making it impossible to distinguish which step failed during debugging.

## What goes wrong
When debugging a crypto failure, the log message provides no indication of which step failed. In practice, `tc_sha256_*` functions rarely fail (they check for NULL internally and the state is valid), so this is low-impact.

## Recommendation
For debugging, consider separating into individual calls with distinct error codes or LOG_ERR messages. Example:
```c
if (tc_sha256_init(&state) != TC_CRYPTO_SUCCESS) {
    LOG_ERR("SHA-256 init failed");
    ret = -EIO; goto cleanup;
}
// etc.
```
